<div class="thumbcaption">
<p>Proportions of first-language speakers<sup about="#mwt390" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEChinese_Academy_of_Social_Sciences20123_1-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTEChinese Academy of Social Sciences20123"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEChinese_Academy_of_Social_Sciences20123-1"}}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEChinese_Academy_of_Social_Sciences20123-1" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[1]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#ac8761; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mandarin_Chinese" title="Mandarin Chinese">Mandarin</a> (66.2%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#b1bab6; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Min_Chinese" title="Min Chinese">Min</a> (6.2%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#c8c8a8; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wu_Chinese" title="Wu Chinese">Wu</a> (6.1%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#96642c; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jin_Chinese" title="Jin Chinese">Jin</a> (5.2%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#bf6e7b; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yue_Chinese" title="Yue Chinese">Yue</a> (4.9%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#fbd98d; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gan_Chinese" title="Gan Chinese">Gan</a> (4.0%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#eeb36a; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hakka_Chinese" title="Hakka Chinese">Hakka</a> (3.5%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#a5ae87; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Xiang_Chinese" title="Xiang Chinese">Xiang</a> (3.0%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#9b987f; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Huizhou_Chinese" title="Huizhou Chinese">Huizhou</a> (0.3%)</div><div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color:
#946565; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pinghua" title="Pinghua">Pinghua</a>, others (0.6%)</div>
</div>
</div></div>
<p id="mw8g">Local varieties of Chinese are conventionally classified into seven dialect groups, largely on the basis of the different evolution of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Middle_Chinese" title="Middle Chinese" id="mw8w">Middle Chinese</a> voiced initials:<sup about="#mwt71" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman1988181_47-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Norman"},"2":{"wt":"1988"},"p":{"wt":"181"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman1988181-47" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 46;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[46]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt72" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKurpaska201053–55_48-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kurpaska"},"2":{"wt":"2010"},"pp":{"wt":"53–55"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKurpaska201053–55-48" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 47;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[47]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul id="mw9A"><li id="mw9Q"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mandarin_Chinese" title="Mandarin Chinese" id="mw9g">Mandarin</a>, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Chinese" title="Standard Chinese" id="mw9w">Standard Chinese</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Beijing_dialect" title="Beijing dialect" id="mw-A">Pekinese</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sichuanese_Mandarin" title="Sichuanese Mandarin" id="mw-Q" class="mw-redirect">Sichuanese</a>, and also the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dungan_language" title="Dungan language" id="mw-g">Dungan language</a> spoken in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Central_Asia" title="Central Asia" id="mw-w">Central Asia</a></li>
<li id="mw_A"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wu_Chinese" title="Wu Chinese" id="mw_Q">Wu</a>, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shanghainese_dialect" title="Shanghainese dialect" id="mw_g" class="mw-redirect">Shanghainese</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Suzhou_dialect" title="Suzhou dialect" id="mw_w">Suzhounese</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wenzhounese" title="Wenzhounese" id="mwAQA">Wenzhounese</a></li>
<li id="mwAQE"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gan_Chinese" title="Gan Chinese" id="mwAQI">Gan</a></li>
<li id="mwAQM"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Xiang_Chinese" title="Xiang Chinese" id="mwAQQ">Xiang</a></li>
<li id="mwAQU"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Min_Chinese" title="Min Chinese" id="mwAQY">Min</a>, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fuzhou_dialect" title="Fuzhou dialect" id="mwAQc">Fuzhounese</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hainanese" title="Hainanese" id="mwAQg">Hainanese</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hokkien" title="Hokkien" id="mwAQk">Hokkien</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwanese_Hokkien" title="Taiwanese Hokkien" id="mwAQo">Taiwanese</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Teochew_dialect" title="Teochew dialect" id="mwAQs">Teochew</a></li>
<li id="mwAQw"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hakka_Chinese" title="Hakka Chinese" id="mwAQ0">Hakka</a></li>
<li id="mwAQ4"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yue_Chinese" title="Yue Chinese" id="mwAQ8">Yue</a>, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cantonese" title="Cantonese" id="mwARA">Cantonese</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taishanese" title="Taishanese" id="mwARE">Taishanese</a></li></ul>

<p id="mwARI">The classification of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Li_Rong_(linguist)" title="Li Rong (linguist)" id="mwARM">Li Rong</a>, which is used in the <i id="mwARQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Language_Atlas_of_China" title="Language Atlas of China" id="mwARU">Language Atlas of China</a></i> (1987), distinguishes three further groups:<sup about="#mwt73" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWurmLiBaumannLee1987_40-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Wurm"},"2":{"wt":"Li"},"3":{"wt":"Baumann"},"4":{"wt":"Lee"},"5":{"wt":"1987"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWurmLiBaumannLee1987-40" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[39]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt74" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKurpaska201055–56_49-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kurpaska"},"2":{"wt":"2010"},"pp":{"wt":"55–56"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKurpaska201055–56-49" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 48;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[48]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul id="mwARY"><li id="mwARc"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jin_Chinese" title="Jin Chinese" id="mwARg">Jin</a>, previously included in Mandarin.</li>
<li id="mwARk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Huizhou_Chinese" title="Huizhou Chinese" id="mwARo">Huizhou</a>, previously included in Wu.</li>
<li id="mwARs"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pinghua_Chinese" title="Pinghua Chinese" id="mwARw" class="mw-redirect">Pinghua</a>, previously included in Yue.</li></ul>

<p id="mwAR0">Some varieties remain unclassified, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Danzhou_dialect" title="Danzhou dialect" id="mwAR4">Danzhou dialect</a> (spoken in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Danzhou" title="Danzhou" id="mwAR8">Danzhou</a>, on <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hainan" title="Hainan" id="mwASA">Hainan</a> Island), <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Waxianghua" title="Waxianghua" id="mwASE" class="mw-redirect">Waxianghua</a> (spoken in western <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hunan" title="Hunan" id="mwASI">Hunan</a>) and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shaozhou_Tuhua" title="Shaozhou Tuhua" id="mwASM">Shaozhou Tuhua</a> (spoken in northern <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Guangdong" title="Guangdong" id="mwASQ">Guangdong</a>).<sup about="#mwt75" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKurpaska201072–73_50-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kurpaska"},"2":{"wt":"2010"},"pp":{"wt":"72–73"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKurpaska201072–73-50" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 49;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[49]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="9" id="mwASU"><h3 id="Standard_Chinese">Standard Chinese</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt76" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Standard Chinese"},"2":{"wt":"List of countries where Chinese is an official language"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwASY">Main articles: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Chinese" title="Standard Chinese">Standard Chinese</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./List_of_countries_where_Chinese_is_an_official_language" title="List of countries where Chinese is an official language" class="mw-redirect">List of countries where Chinese is an official language</a></div>
<!--This is a SUMMARY. Please add new information to [[Standard Chinese]].-->
<p id="mwASc"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Chinese" title="Standard Chinese" id="mwASg">Standard Chinese</a>, often called Mandarin, is the official <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_language" title="Standard language" id="mwASk">standard language</a> of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./China" title="China" id="mwASo">China</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwan" title="Taiwan" id="mwASs">Taiwan</a>, and one of the four official languages of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Singapore" title="Singapore" id="mwASw">Singapore</a> (where it is called "Huáyŭ" <span lang="zh-Hans" title="Chinese language text" about="#mwt77" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang","href":"./Template:Lang"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"zh-Hans"},"2":{"wt":"华语"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAS0">华语</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" about="#mwt77" id="mwAS4"/> or simply Chinese). Standard Chinese is based on the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Beijing_dialect" title="Beijing dialect" id="mwAS8">Beijing dialect</a>, the dialect of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mandarin_Chinese" title="Mandarin Chinese" id="mwATA">Mandarin</a> as spoken in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Beijing" title="Beijing" id="mwATE">Beijing</a>. The governments of both China and Taiwan intend for speakers of all Chinese speech varieties to use it as a common language of communication. Therefore, it is used in government agencies, in the media, and as a language of instruction in schools.</p>

<p id="mwATI">In <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mainland_China" title="Mainland China" id="mwATM">mainland China</a> and Taiwan, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diglossia" title="Diglossia" id="mwATQ">diglossia</a> has been a common feature. For example, in addition to Standard Chinese, a resident of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shanghai" title="Shanghai" id="mwATU">Shanghai</a> might speak <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shanghainese" title="Shanghainese" id="mwATY">Shanghainese</a>; and, if he or she grew up elsewhere, then he or she is also likely to be fluent in the particular dialect of that local area. A native of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Guangzhou" title="Guangzhou" id="mwATc">Guangzhou</a> may speak both Cantonese and Standard Chinese. In addition to Mandarin, most <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwanese_people" title="Taiwanese people" id="mwATg">Taiwanese</a> also speak <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwanese_Hokkien" title="Taiwanese Hokkien" id="mwATk">Minnan</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hakka_language" title="Hakka language" id="mwATo" class="mw-redirect">Hakka</a>, or an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Austronesian_languages" title="Austronesian languages" id="mwATs">Austronesian language</a>.<sup about="#mwt692" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-51" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-51"}}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-51" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 50;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[50]</span></a></sup> A Taiwanese may commonly mix pronunciations, phrases, and words from Mandarin and other <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Languages_of_Taiwan" title="Languages of Taiwan" id="mwATw">Taiwanese languages</a>, and this mixture is considered normal in daily or informal speech.<sup about="#mwt694" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-52" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-52"}}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-52" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 51;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[51]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="10" id="mwAT0"><h3 id="Nomenclature">Nomenclature</h3>
<p id="mwAT4">The official Chinese designation for the major branches of Chinese is <i id="mwAT8">fāngyán</i> (<span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" about="#mwt82" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang","href":"./Template:Lang"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"zh"},"2":{"wt":"方言"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAUA">方言</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" about="#mwt82" id="mwAUE"/>, literally "regional speech"), whereas the more closely related varieties within these are called <i id="mwAUI">dìdiǎn fāngyán</i> (<span lang="zh-Hans" title="Chinese language text" about="#mwt83" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang","href":"./Template:Lang"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"zh-hans"},"2":{"wt":"地点方言"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAUM">地点方言</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" about="#mwt83" id="mwAUQ"/>/<span lang="zh-Hant" title="Chinese language text" about="#mwt84" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang","href":"./Template:Lang"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"zh-hant"},"2":{"wt":"地點方言"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAUU">地點方言</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" about="#mwt84" id="mwAUY"/> "local speech").<sup about="#mwt85" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198457_53-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"DeFrancis"},"2":{"wt":"1984"},"p":{"wt":"57"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198457-53" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 52;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[52]</span></a></sup>  Conventional English-language usage in Chinese linguistics is to use <i id="mwAUc">dialect</i> for the speech of a particular place (regardless of status) and <i id="mwAUg">dialect group</i> for a regional grouping such as Mandarin or Wu.<sup about="#mwt86" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman200372_41-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Norman"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"72"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman200372-41" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[40]</span></a></sup>  Because varieties from different groups are not <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mutually_intelligible" title="Mutually intelligible" id="mwAUk" class="mw-redirect">mutually intelligible</a>, some scholars prefer to describe Wu and others as separate languages.<sup about="#mwt87" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEThomason198827–28_54-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Thomason"},"2":{"wt":"1988"},"pp":{"wt":"27–28"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEThomason198827–28-54" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 53;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[53]</span></a></sup><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:All_articles_lacking_reliable_references" about="#mwt88" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"better source","href":"./Template:Better_source"},"params":{"reason":{"wt":"This claim needs a source specifically saying that scholars do this and for this reason"},"date":{"wt":"June 2015"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAUo"/><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_lacking_reliable_references_from_June_2015" about="#mwt88"/><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;" about="#mwt88" id="mwAUs"><span typeof="mw:Entity">[</span><i><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wikipedia:NOTRS" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS" class="mw-redirect"><span title="This claim needs a source specifically saying that scholars do this and for this reason (June 2015)">better<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>source<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>needed</span></a></i><span typeof="mw:Entity">]</span></sup> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jerry_Norman_(sinologist)" title="Jerry Norman (sinologist)" id="mwAUw">Jerry Norman</a> called this practice misleading, pointing out that Wu, which itself contains many mutually unintelligible varieties, could not be properly called a single language under the same criterion, and that the same is true for each of the other groups.<sup about="#mwt89" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman200372_41-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Norman"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"72"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman200372-41" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[40]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAU0">Mutual intelligibility is considered by some linguists to be the main criterion for determining whether varieties are separate languages or dialects of a single language,<sup about="#mwt90" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMair199117_55-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Mair"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"17"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMair199117-55" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 54;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[54]</span></a></sup> although others do not regard it as decisive,<sup about="#mwt91" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198454_56-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"DeFrancis"},"2":{"wt":"1984"},"p":{"wt":"54"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198454-56" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 55;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[55]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt92" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERomaine200013,_23_57-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Romaine"},"2":{"wt":"2000"},"pp":{"wt":"13, 23"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTERomaine200013,_23-57" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 56;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[56]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt93" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWardaughFuller201428–32_58-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Wardaugh"},"2":{"wt":"Fuller"},"3":{"wt":"2014"},"pp":{"wt":"28–32"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWardaughFuller201428–32-58" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 57;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[57]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt94" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELiang201411–14_59-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Liang"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"pp":{"wt":"11–14"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTELiang201411–14-59" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 58;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[58]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt95" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHymes197164_60-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Hymes"},"2":{"wt":"1971"},"p":{"wt":"64"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHymes197164-60" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 59;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[59]</span></a></sup> particularly when cultural factors interfere as they do with Chinese.<sup about="#mwt96" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEThomason198827_61-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Thomason"},"2":{"wt":"1988"},"p":{"wt":"27"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEThomason198827-61" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 60;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[60]</span></a></sup> As <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chinese_language#CITEREFCampbell2008" about="#mwt97" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Harvcoltxt","href":"./Template:Harvcoltxt"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Campbell"},"2":{"wt":"2008"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAU4">Campbell (2008)</a> explains, linguists often ignore mutual intelligibility when varieties share intelligibility with a central variety (i.e. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Prestige_variety" title="Prestige variety" id="mwAU8" class="mw-redirect">prestige variety</a>, such as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Mandarin" title="Standard Mandarin" id="mwAVA" class="mw-redirect">Standard Mandarin</a>), as the issue requires some careful handling when mutual intelligibility is inconsistent with language identity.<sup about="#mwt98" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTECampbell2008637_62-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Campbell"},"2":{"wt":"2008"},"p":{"wt":"637"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTECampbell2008637-62" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 61;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[61]</span></a></sup> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./John_DeFrancis" title="John DeFrancis" id="mwAVE">John DeFrancis</a> argues that it is inappropriate to refer to Mandarin, Wu and so on as "dialects" because the mutual unintelligibility between them is too great. On the other hand, he also objects to considering them as separate languages, as it incorrectly implies a set of disruptive "religious, economic, political, and other differences" between speakers that exist, for example, between <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./French_language_in_Canada" title="French language in Canada" id="mwAVI">French Catholics</a> and English Protestants in Canada, but not between speakers of Cantonese and Mandarin in China, owing to China's near-uninterrupted history of centralized government.<sup about="#mwt99" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198455–57_63-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"DeFrancis"},"2":{"wt":"1984"},"pp":{"wt":"55–57"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198455–57-63" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 62;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[62]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAVM">Because of the difficulties involved in determining the difference between language and dialect, other terms have been proposed: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./ISO_639-3" title="ISO 639-3" id="mwAVQ">ISO 639-3</a> follows <i id="mwAVU"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ethnologue" title="Ethnologue" id="mwAVY">Ethnologue</a></i> in assigning individual language codes to the 13 main subdivisions, while Chinese as a whole is classified as a '<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Macrolanguage" title="Macrolanguage" id="mwAVc" class="mw-redirect">macrolanguage</a>'.<sup about="#mwt101" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELewisSimonsFennig2015_64-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Lewis"},"2":{"wt":"Simons"},"3":{"wt":"Fennig"},"4":{"wt":"2015"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTELewisSimonsFennig2015-64" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 63;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[63]</span></a></sup> Other options include <i id="mwAVg">vernacular</i>,<sup about="#mwt102" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHaugen1966927_65-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Haugen"},"2":{"wt":"1966"},"p":{"wt":"927"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHaugen1966927-65" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 64;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[64]</span></a></sup> <i id="mwAVk">lect</i> <sup about="#mwt611" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-66" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-66"}}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-66" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 65;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[65]</span></a></sup> <i id="mwAVo">regionalect</i>,<sup about="#mwt105" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198457_53-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"DeFrancis"},"2":{"wt":"1984"},"p":{"wt":"57"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDeFrancis198457-53" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 52;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[52]</span></a></sup> <i id="mwAVs">topolect</i>,<sup about="#mwt106" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMair19917_67-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Mair"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMair19917-67" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 66;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[66]</span></a></sup> and <i id="mwAVw">variety</i>.<sup about="#mwt107" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHudson199622_68-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Hudson"},"2":{"wt":"1996"},"p":{"wt":"22"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHudson199622-68" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 67;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[67]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAV0">Most Chinese people consider the spoken varieties as one single language because speakers share a common culture and history, as well as a shared national identity and a common written form.<sup about="#mwt108" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBaxter19927–8_69-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Baxter"},"2":{"wt":"1992"},"p":{"wt":"7–8"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBaxter19927–8-69" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 68;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[68]</span></a></sup> To Chinese nationalists, the idea of Chinese as a language family may suggest that the Chinese identity is much more fragmented and disunified than it actually is and as such is often looked upon as culturally and politically provocative. Additionally, <span class="citation-needed-content" style="padding-left:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em; color:#595959; border:1px solid #DDD;" about="#mwt109" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"citation needed span","href":"./Template:Citation_needed_span"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"in [[Taiwan]] it is closely associated with [[Taiwanese independence]],"},"date":{"wt":"June 2015"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAV4">in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwan" title="Taiwan">Taiwan</a> it is closely associated with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwanese_independence" title="Taiwanese independence" class="mw-redirect">Taiwanese independence</a>,</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:All_articles_with_unsourced_statements" about="#mwt109"/><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_unsourced_statements_from_June_2015" about="#mwt109"/><sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;" about="#mwt109" id="mwAV8"><span typeof="mw:Entity">[</span><i><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (June 2015)" about="#mwt612" typeof="mw:ExpandedAttrs" data-mw='{"attribs":[[{"txt":"title"},{"html":"This claim needs references to reliable sources.&lt;span typeof=\"mw:Nowiki\" data-parsoid=\"{}\">&lt;/span> (June 2015)"}]]}'>citation needed</span></a></i><span typeof="mw:Entity">]</span></sup> some of whose supporters promote the local <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Taiwanese_Hokkien" title="Taiwanese Hokkien" id="mwAWA">Taiwanese Hokkien</a> variety.</p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="11" id="mwAWE"><h2 id="Phonology">Phonology</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt110" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"see also","href":"./Template:See_also"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Standard Chinese phonology"},"2":{"wt":"Historical Chinese phonology"},"3":{"wt":"Varieties of Chinese#Phonology"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAWI">See also: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Chinese_phonology" title="Standard Chinese phonology">Standard Chinese phonology</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Historical_Chinese_phonology" title="Historical Chinese phonology">Historical Chinese phonology</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Varieties_of_Chinese#Phonology" title="Varieties of Chinese">Varieties of Chinese §<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>Phonology</a></div>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-default-audio-height" typeof="mw:Audio/Thumb" id="mwAWM"><span id="mwAWQ"><audio controls="" preload="none" height="32" width="220" resource="./File:Edmund_Yeo_-_voice_-_ch_150127_1828.wav" id="mwAWU"><source src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/27/Edmund_Yeo_-_voice_-_ch_150127_1828.wav" type="audio/wav" data-title="Original WAV file (768 kbps)" data-shorttitle="WAV source" id="mwAWY"/><source src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/2/27/Edmund_Yeo_-_voice_-_ch_150127_1828.wav/Edmund_Yeo_-_voice_-_ch_150127_1828.wav.mp3" type="audio/mpeg" data-title="MP3" data-shorttitle="MP3" id="mwAWc"/><source src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/2/27/Edmund_Yeo_-_voice_-_ch_150127_1828.wav/Edmund_Yeo_-_voice_-_ch_150127_1828.wav.ogg" type='audio/ogg; codecs="vorbis"' data-title="Ogg Vorbis" data-shorttitle="Ogg Vorbis" id="mwAWg"/></audio></span><figcaption id="mwAWk">Spoken <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mandarin_Chinese" title="Mandarin Chinese" id="mwAWo">Mandarin Chinese</a></figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAWs">The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Phonology" title="Phonology" id="mwAWw">phonological</a> structure of each syllable consists of a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Syllable_nucleus" title="Syllable nucleus" id="mwAW0" class="mw-redirect">nucleus</a> that has a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vowel" title="Vowel" id="mwAW4">vowel</a> (which can be a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Monophthong" title="Monophthong" id="mwAW8">monophthong</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diphthong" title="Diphthong" id="mwAXA">diphthong</a>, or even a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Triphthong" title="Triphthong" id="mwAXE">triphthong</a> in certain varieties), preceded by an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Syllable_onset" title="Syllable onset" id="mwAXI" class="mw-redirect">onset</a> (a single <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Consonant" title="Consonant" id="mwAXM">consonant</a>, or consonant+<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Semivowel" title="Semivowel" id="mwAXQ">glide</a>; zero onset is also possible), and followed (optionally) by a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Syllable_coda" title="Syllable coda" id="mwAXU" class="mw-redirect">coda</a> consonant; a syllable also carries a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tone_(linguistics)" title="Tone (linguistics)" id="mwAXY">tone</a>. There are some instances where a vowel is not used as a nucleus. An example of this is in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cantonese" title="Cantonese" id="mwAXc">Cantonese</a>, where the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nasal_stop" title="Nasal stop" id="mwAXg" class="mw-redirect">nasal</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sonorant" title="Sonorant" id="mwAXk">sonorant</a> consonants <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt111" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/m/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAXo">/m/</span> and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt112" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/ŋ/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAXs">/ŋ/</span> can stand alone as their own syllable.</p>

<p id="mwAXw">In Mandarin much more than in other spoken varieties, most syllables tend to be open syllables, meaning they have no coda (assuming that a final <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Semivowel" title="Semivowel" id="mwAX0">glide</a> is not analyzed as a coda), but syllables that do have codas are restricted to nasals <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt113" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/m/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAX4">/m/</span>, <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt114" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/n/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAX8">/n/</span>, <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt115" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/ŋ/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYA">/ŋ/</span>, the retroflex approximant <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt116" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/ɻ /"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYE">/ɻ /</span>, and voiceless stops <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt117" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/p/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYI">/p/</span>, <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt118" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/t/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYM">/t/</span>, <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt119" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/k/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYQ">/k/</span>, or <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt120" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/ʔ/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYU">/ʔ/</span>. Some varieties allow most of these codas, whereas others, such as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Chinese" title="Standard Chinese" id="mwAYY">Standard Chinese</a>, are limited to only <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt121" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/n/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYc">/n/</span>, <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt122" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/ŋ/"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYg">/ŋ/</span> and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA" about="#mwt123" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPA","href":"./Template:IPA"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"/ɻ /"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYk">/ɻ /</span>.</p>

<p id="mwAYo">The number of sounds in the different spoken dialects varies, but in general there has been a tendency to a reduction in sounds from <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Middle_Chinese" title="Middle Chinese" id="mwAYs">Middle Chinese</a>. The Mandarin dialects in particular have experienced a dramatic decrease in sounds and so have far more multisyllabic words than most other spoken varieties. The total number of syllables in some varieties is therefore only about a thousand, including tonal variation, which is only about an eighth as many as English.<sup about="#mwt124" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-DeFrancis_p42_70-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"efn","href":"./Template:Efn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"{{harvtxt|DeFrancis|1984}} p.42 counts Chinese as having 1,277 tonal syllables, and about 398 to 418 if tones are disregarded; he cites Jespersen, Otto (1928) &apos;&apos;Monosyllabism in English&apos;&apos;; London, p.15 for a count of over 8000 syllables for English."},"name":{"wt":"DeFrancis p42"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-DeFrancis_p42-70" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;" data-mw-group="lower-alpha"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[lower-alpha 2]</span></a></sup></p>

<section data-mw-section-id="12" id="mwAYw"><h3 id="Tones">Tones</h3>
<p id="mwAY0">All varieties of spoken Chinese use <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tone_(linguistics)" title="Tone (linguistics)" id="mwAY4">tones</a> to distinguish words.<sup about="#mwt128" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-71" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"group":"note"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-71"}}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-71" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;" data-mw-group="note"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[note 1]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt126" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorman198852_72-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnp","href":"./Template:Sfnp"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Norman"},"2":{"wt":"1988"},"p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Chinese_language#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorman198852-72" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 69;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[69]</span></a></sup> A few dialects of north China may have as few as three tones, while some dialects in south China have up to 6 or 12 tones, depending on how one counts. One exception from this is <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shanghainese_dialect" title="Shanghainese dialect" id="mwAY8" class="mw-redirect">Shanghainese</a> which has reduced the set of tones to a two-toned <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pitch_accent" title="Pitch accent" id="mwAZA" class="mw-redirect">pitch accent</a> system much like modern Japanese.</p>

<p id="mwAZE">A very common example used to illustrate the use of tones in Chinese is the application of the four tones of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Standard_Chinese" title="Standard Chinese" id="mwAZI">Standard Chinese</a> (along with the neutral tone) to the syllable <i id="mwAZM">ma</i>. The tones are exemplified by the following five Chinese words:</p>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r856303569" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" about="#mwt129" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Chinese tones","href":"./Template:Chinese_tones"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAZQ">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class="thumb tmulti tright" about="#mwt129"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:232px;max-width:232px"><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:60px;max-width:60px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:69px;overflow:hidden"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:First_tone_(Mandarin).png"><img alt="" resource="./File:First_tone_(Mandarin).png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/First_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/58px-First_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png" data-file-width="339" data-file-height="402" data-file-type="bitmap" height="69" width="58" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/First_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/116px-First_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/First_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/87px-First_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div></div><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:52px;max-width:52px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:69px;overflow:hidden"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Second_tone_(Mandarin).png"><img alt="" resource="./File:Second_tone_(Mandarin).png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Second_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/50px-Second_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png" data-file-width="288" data-file-height="398" data-file-type="bitmap" height="69" width="50" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Second_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/100px-Second_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Second_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/75px-Second_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div></div><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:67px;max-width:67px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:69px;overflow:hidden"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Third_tone_(Mandarin).png"><img alt="" resource="./File:Third_tone_(Mandarin).png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Third_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/65px-Third_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png" data-file-width="373" data-file-height="398" data-file-type="bitmap" height="69" width="65" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Third_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/130px-Third_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Third_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/98px-Third_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div></div><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:45px;max-width:45px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:69px;overflow:hidden"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Fourth_tone_(Mandarin).png"><img alt="" resource="./File:Fourth_tone_(Mandarin).png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Fourth_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/43px-Fourth_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png" data-file-width="247" data-file-height="400" data-file-type="bitmap" height="70" width="43" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Fourth_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/86px-Fourth_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Fourth_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png/65px-Fourth_tone_%28Mandarin%29.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div></div><div style="clear:left"></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left;text-align:left;background-color:transparent">The four main tones of Standard Mandarin, pronounced with the syllable <i>ma</i>.<div style="width:100%; height:10px"></div><figure class="mw-halign-center mw-default-audio-height" typeof="mw:Audio"><span><audio controls="" preload="none" height="32" width="220" resource="./File:Zh-pinyin_tones_with_ma.ogg"><source src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/64/Zh-pinyin_tones_with_ma.ogg" type='audio/ogg; codecs="vorbis"' data-title="Original Ogg file (64 kbps)" data-shorttitle="Ogg source"/><source src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/6/64/Zh-pinyin_tones_with_ma.ogg/Zh-pinyin_tones_with_ma.ogg.mp3" type="audio/mpeg" data-title="MP3" data-shorttitle="MP3"/></audio></span><figcaption></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Pages_using_multiple_image_with_auto_scaled_images" about="#mwt129" id="mwAZU"/>
